+{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01B97RdoZ6U2MqBYPqCmTg3r","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→export interface Gate {\n     2→  op: 'AND' | 'OR' | 'XOR';\n     3→  in1: string;\n     4→  in2: string;\n     5→  out: string;\n     6→}\n     7→\n     8→/**\n     9→ * Simulate a circuit: given gates and initial wire values, compute all wire values.\n    10→ */\n    11→export function simulate(\n    12→  gates: Gate[],\n    13→  inputs: Record<string, number>\n    14→): Record<string, number> {\n    15→  const wires: Record<string, number> = { ...inputs };\n    16→  const remaining = [...gates];\n    17→\n    18→  let changed = true;\n    19→  while (remaining.length > 0 && changed) {\n    20→    changed = false;\n    21→    for (let i = remaining.length - 1; i >= 0; i--) {\n    22→      const gate = remaining[i];\n    23→      const v1 = wires[gate.in1];\n    24→      const v2 = wires[gate.in2];\n    25→      if (v1 !== undefined && v2 !== undefined) {\n    26→        let result: number;\n    27→        switch (gate.op) {\n    28→          case 'AND':\n    29→            result = v1 & v2;\n    30→            break;\n    31→          case 'OR':\n    32→            result = v1 | v2;\n    33→            break;\n    34→          case 'XOR':\n    35→            result = v1 ^ v2;\n    36→            break;\n    37→        }\n    38→        wires[gate.out] = result;\n    39→        remaining.splice(i, 1);\n    40→        changed = true;\n    41→      }\n    42→    }\n    43→  }\n    44→\n    45→  return wires;\n    46→}"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_019GAdzrxr6cBxLhMy1KAW13","session_id":"1e1eb691-2963-482c-977e-888575e0a645","uuid":"042a9a53-b696-4186-b1b0-8d83454012cf"}
+{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_019GAdzrxr6cBxLhMy1KAW13","type":"tool_result","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Now I have a thorough understanding of the code. Here is my complete review:\n\n---\n\n## Code Review: Circuit Simulator and Wire-Swap Debugger\n\n### HIGH PRIORITY\n\n#### 1. `simulate`: `result` variable used before definite assignment (line 38)\n\n**File:** `/workspace/src/index.ts`, lines 26-38\n\n```typescript\nlet result: number;\nswitch (gate.op) {\n  case 'AND': result = v1 & v2; break;\n  case 'OR':  result = v1 | v2; break;\n  case 'XOR': result = v1 ^ v2; break;\n}\nwires[gate.out] = result; // TypeScript strict: possibly unassigned\n```\n\nThe `switch` statement has no `default` case. While the `Gate` type constrains `op` to `'AND' | 'OR' | 'XOR'`, TypeScript's control flow analysis with `let result: number` and no `default` branch means `result` is technically possibly unassigned at line 38. Under `strict` / `strictNullChecks`, some TS configurations will flag this. More importantly, if the type system is ever circumvented (e.g., casting from parsed JSON), an unrecognized op would silently produce `undefined` being stored as a wire value, leading to downstream corruption rather than a clear error.\n\n**Recommendation:** Add a `default` case that throws an error, or initialize `result` to a sentinel and assert:\n\n```typescript\ndefault:\n  throw new Error(`Unknown gate operation: ${(gate as any).op}`);\n```\n\n#### 2. `simulate`: O(n^2) performance from `Array.splice` in a loop (lines 39, 21)\n\n**File:** `/workspace/src/index.ts`, line 39\n\n```typescript\nremaining.splice(i, 1);\n```\n\n`Array.splice` is O(n) because it shifts all subsequent elements. In the inner loop iterating over `remaining`, this produces O(n^2) behavior in the worst case across passes. For a 45-bit adder with ~220 gates, this is ~48,400 operations per pass -- manageable but wasteful. For larger circuits this would become a bottleneck.\n\n**Recommendation:** Use a `Set` of unprocessed gate indices, or rebuild the remaining array once per pass by filtering, or use topological sort for O(V+E) evaluation:\n\n```typescript\n// Option A: filter instead of splice\nconst nextRemaining: Gate[] = [];\nfor (const gate of remaining) {\n  // ... try to evaluate ...\n  if (!evaluated) nextRemaining.push(gate);\n}\nremaining = nextRemaining;\n```\n\n**Severity for 220 gates:** Low in practice (tests pass in <10ms), but the algorithmic concern is real.\n\n#### 3. `findSwappedWires`: Null dereference when `sumGate` is null at line 219\n\n**File:** `/workspace/src/index.ts`, line 219\n\n```typescript\nif (sumGate.out !== zw) doSwap(sumGate.out, zw);\n```\n\nThere is an explicit `if (!sumGate) throw new Error(...)` on line 216 that guards this. However, in the diff version shown in the problem statement, the `throw` guard on line 216 was **absent** -- the code jumped straight to `if (sumGate.out !== zw)`. Looking at the actual file, line 216 does contain the guard. The diff in the problem statement is a condensed version that omits lines 148 and 216, meaning **the diff as provided in the problem statement has a null-dereference bug at `sumGate.out`**. The actual source file is correct. This is worth flagging because if the diff is the source of truth, it is a crash.\n\nIn the diff:\n```diff\n+      if (!sumGate) {\n+        ...\n+      }\n+\n+      if (sumGate.out !== zw) doSwap(sumGate.out, zw);\n```\n\nBetween the last `if (!sumGate)` block (which does not throw or return) and line `if (sumGate.out !== zw)`, the variable `sumGate` can still be `undefined` if none of the three search strategies found a gate. The real file has a `throw` that prevents this, but in the diff it is missing.\n\n#### 4. `findSwappedWires`: Mutates the input `gates` array's objects (lines 117-118)\n\n**File:** `/workspace/src/index.ts`, lines 111-121\n\n```typescript\nfunction doSwap(wire1: string, wire2: string): void {\n  swapped.add(wire1);\n  swapped.add(wire2);\n  const g1 = gateByOutput.get(wire1)!;\n  const g2 = gateByOutput.get(wire2)!;\n  g1.out = wire2;  // Mutates the original Gate object\n  g2.out = wire1;  // Mutates the original Gate object\n  gateByOutput.set(wire1, g2);\n  gateByOutput.set(wire2, g1);\n}\n```\n\n`doSwap` mutates the `out` property of Gate objects from the input array. This means after `findSwappedWires` returns, the caller's `gates` array has been permanently modified. This is a surprising side effect for a function that appears to be a pure query (\"find swapped wires\"). If the caller subsequently uses the gates for simulation or calls `findSwappedWires` again, the gates are in a different state.\n\n**Recommendation:** Deep-clone the gates array at the top of `findSwappedWires`:\n\n```typescript\nconst gates = inputGates.map(g => ({ ...g }));\n```\n\n#### 5. `findSwappedWires`: `findGate` is O(n) linear scan, called multiple times per bit (lines 76-91)\n\n**File:** `/workspace/src/index.ts`, lines 76-91\n\n```typescript\nfunction findGate(op: string, in1: string, in2: string): Gate | undefined {\n  for (const g of gates) {\n    if (g.op === op && ((g.in1 === in1 && g.in2 === in2) || (g.in1 === in2 && g.in2 === in1))) {\n      return g;\n    }\n  }\n  return undefined;\n}\n```\n\n`findGate` does a linear scan over all ~220 gates every time it is called. It is called at least 4 times per bit (for XOR, XOR, AND, AND, OR), so for 45 bits that is ~220 * 45 * 5 = ~49,500 comparisons. This is fine for the current scale, but a `Map<string, Gate>` keyed on `{op}-{sorted_inputs}` would make each lookup O(1).\n\n**Severity for 220 gates:** Low (tests pass in <10ms), but worth noting for scalability.\n\n---\n\n### MEDIUM PRIORITY\n\n#### 6. `simulate`: Silent failure on unsolvable circuits\n\n**File:** `/workspace/src/index.ts`, lines 18-43\n\nIf gates have a dependency cycle or reference wires that never receive values, the `while` loop exits silently (when `changed` becomes `false` with `remaining.length > 0`). The function returns a partial result with no indication that some gates were not evaluated.\n\n**Recommendation:** After the loop, if `remaining.length > 0`, either throw an error or return the remaining gates alongside the partial result so the caller can detect the issue:\n\n```typescript\nif (remaining.length > 0) {\n  throw new Error(`${remaining.length} gates could not be evaluated (cycle or missing inputs)`);\n}\n```\n\n#### 7. `findSwappedWires`: `doSwap` does not update `findGate` search results\n\n**File:** `/workspace/src/index.ts`, lines 111-121 and 76-91\n\n`doSwap` updates `gateByOutput` (the output-to-gate map), but `findGate` searches by `(op, in1, in2)` -- it does not search by output. Since `doSwap` only changes `.out` properties and not `.in1`/`.in2`, `findGate` is unaffected. This is correct as-is, but the fact that the `gates` array is mutated (`.out` changes) means `findGate` is implicitly relying on the invariant that swaps only change outputs, never inputs. This is fragile and should be documented.\n\n#### 8. `findSwappedWires`: Missing null guard on `xorGate` for bit > 0\n\n**File:** `/workspace/src/index.ts`, line 147-149\n\n```typescript\nconst xorGate = findGate('XOR', xw, yw);\nif (!xorGate) throw new Error(`Missing XOR gate for bit ${bit}`);\nlet partialSum = xorGate.out;\n```\n\nThis is correctly guarded with a `throw`. Good. However, the `andGate` on line 224 and `propGate` on line 229 also have guards. What is missing is consideration of whether a swap earlier in the trace could have *moved* the XOR gate's output wire, causing `findGate('XOR', xw, yw)` to fail to find a gate it should find. Since `findGate` searches by `in1`/`in2` (which are never mutated by `doSwap`), this is actually safe. But it is worth verifying mentally that this invariant holds.\n\n#### 9. `findSwappedWires`: No handling of final carry wire (`z{numBits}`)\n\n**File:** `/workspace/src/index.ts`, lines 126-262\n\nAfter the loop, the last `carry` wire should be the output `z{numBits}` (e.g., `z45` for a 45-bit adder). The code does not verify this. If the carry wire was swapped with some other wire, this swap would go undetected.\n\nLooking at the test helper `makeAdder`, the last carry *is* renamed to `z{numBits}` (line 95 of the test). But `findSwappedWires` never checks that `carry === z{numBits}`. If a swap involved the final carry output, the function would miss it.\n\n**Recommendation:** After the loop, add:\n\n```typescript\nconst finalZ = `z${String(numBits).padStart(2, '0')}`;\nif (carry !== finalZ) {\n  doSwap(carry, finalZ);\n}\n```\n\n#### 10. `findSwappedWires`: Non-null assertions (`!`) on `gateByOutput.get()` in `doSwap`\n\n**File:** `/workspace/src/index.ts`, lines 115-116\n\n```typescript\nconst g1 = gateByOutput.get(wire1)!;\nconst g2 = gateByOutput.get(wire2)!;\n```\n\nIf either wire is not a gate output (e.g., it is an input wire like `x00`), the `!` assertion will suppress the `undefined` and the next lines will crash with a confusing `Cannot set property 'out' of undefined` error. A descriptive error would be better.\n\n---\n\n### CONSIDER\n\n#### 11. TypeScript `result` could use `const` with ternary or immediate return\n\nThe `let result: number` pattern with the switch is verbose. A more concise and safer approach:\n\n```typescript\nconst result =\n  gate.op === 'AND' ? v1 & v2 :\n  gate.op === 'OR'  ? v1 | v2 :\n  v1 ^ v2;\n```\n\nThis also eliminates the unassigned-variable concern from item #1.\n\n#### 12. `findGate` searches the mutated-output `gates` array\n\nAfter `doSwap`, the `gates` array elements have mutated `.out` fields. `findGate` only checks `.op`, `.in1`, `.in2`, so this is safe. But if a future maintainer adds output-based filtering to `findGate`, it would break. Consider adding a comment explaining this.\n\n#### 13. Wire value type is `number` but semantics are boolean\n\nThe `simulate` function uses `number` for wire values and bitwise operators (`&`, `|`, `^`). This works correctly for 0/1 values, but if a caller passes values like `2` or `-1`, the bitwise operations will produce unexpected results. Consider documenting that wire values must be 0 or 1, or adding validation.\n\n#### 14. Test coverage gaps\n\nThe existing tests cover several swap patterns but do not test:\n- A circuit with **no** swaps (should return an empty array)\n- Swaps involving the final carry wire (`z{numBits}` as noted in item #9)\n- Swaps involving the `carry` from a previous bit being swapped with an unrelated wire\n- The `simulate` function with unreachable gates (cycle detection per item #6)\n- The `simulate` function with an empty gates array\n\n---\n\n### Summary\n\n| # | Priority | Issue | Line(s) |\n|---|----------|-------|---------|\n| 1 | HIGH | No `default` in switch -- `result` possibly unassigned | 26-37 |\n| 2 | HIGH | O(n^2) `splice` in simulation loop | 39 |\n| 3 | HIGH | Potential null deref on `sumGate` (in diff version) | 219 |\n| 4 | HIGH | `doSwap` mutates caller's gate objects (surprising side effect) | 111-121 |\n| 5 | HIGH | `findGate` linear scan called ~225 times | 76-91 |\n| 6 | MEDIUM | Silent partial evaluation on cycles/missing inputs | 18-43 |\n| 7 | MEDIUM | `doSwap`/`findGate` coupling relies on undocumented invariant | 76-121 |\n| 8 | MEDIUM | XOR gate search correctness depends on mutation invariant | 147 |\n| 9 | MEDIUM | Final carry wire not verified against `z{numBits}` | 262 |\n| 10 | MEDIUM | Non-null assertions on potentially missing map entries | 115-116 |\n| 11 | CONSIDER | Use ternary/expression for cleaner `result` assignment | 26-37 |\n| 12 | CONSIDER | Document why `findGate` is safe after mutations | 76-91 |\n| 13 | CONSIDER | Wire values are unvalidated -- bitwise ops assume 0/1 | 25-36 |\n| 14 | CONSIDER | Test coverage gaps (no-swap case, final carry, cycles) | tests |\n\nThe most impactful issues to fix are **#1** (add default/throw in switch), **#4** (clone gates to avoid mutation), **#6** (detect unsolvable circuits), and **#9** (verify final carry wire). Items #2 and #5 are performance concerns that are acceptable at 220 gates but would not scale."},{"type":"text","text":"agentId: a660ebb (for resuming to continue this agent's work if needed)\n<usage>total_tokens: 28116\ntool_uses: 9\nduration_ms: 96299</usage>"}]}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"1e1eb691-2963-482c-977e-888575e0a645","uuid":"a8e12278-e030-4a6f-bf81-b8a30b363d6b","tool_use_result":{"status":"completed","prompt":"You are a code reviewer. Review the following diff for a circuit simulator and wire-swap debugger implementation. The task requires:\n\n1. `simulate(gates, inputs)` - Simulate logic gates (AND/OR/XOR) in dependency order\n2. `findSwappedWires(gates)` - Find 8 wires (4 swap pairs) in a broken binary adder circuit\n\nFocus on:\n- Correctness issues (HIGH priority)\n- Performance concerns for 45-bit circuits (~220 gates) \n- Edge cases that could cause failures\n- Code quality issues (MEDIUM priority)\n\nHere is the diff:\n\n```diff\ndiff --git a/src/index.ts b/src/index.ts\nnew file mode 100644\n--- /dev/null\n+++ b/src/index.ts\n@@ -0,0 +1,266 @@\n+export interface Gate {\n+  op: 'AND' | 'OR' | 'XOR';\n+  in1: string;\n+  in2: string;\n+  out: string;\n+}\n+\n+export function simulate(\n+  gates: Gate[],\n+  inputs: Record<string, number>\n+): Record<string, number> {\n+  const wires: Record<string, number> = { ...inputs };\n+  const remaining = [...gates];\n+\n+  let changed = true;\n+  while (remaining.length > 0 && changed) {\n+    changed = false;\n+    for (let i = remaining.length - 1; i >= 0; i--) {\n+      const gate = remaining[i];\n+      const v1 = wires[gate.in1];\n+      const v2 = wires[gate.in2];\n+      if (v1 !== undefined && v2 !== undefined) {\n+        let result: number;\n+        switch (gate.op) {\n+          case 'AND': result = v1 & v2; break;\n+          case 'OR': result = v1 | v2; break;\n+          case 'XOR': result = v1 ^ v2; break;\n+        }\n+        wires[gate.out] = result;\n+        remaining.splice(i, 1);\n+        changed = true;\n+      }\n+    }\n+  }\n+  return wires;\n+}\n+\n+export function findSwappedWires(gates: Gate[]): string[] {\n+  const swapped: Set<string> = new Set();\n+  const gateByOutput: Map<string, Gate> = new Map();\n+  for (const g of gates) gateByOutput.set(g.out, g);\n+\n+  function findGate(op: string, in1: string, in2: string): Gate | undefined {\n+    for (const g of gates) {\n+      if (g.op === op && ((g.in1 === in1 && g.in2 === in2) || (g.in1 === in2 && g.in2 === in1))) {\n+        return g;\n+      }\n+    }\n+    return undefined;\n+  }\n+\n+  function gateFor(out: string): Gate | undefined { return gateByOutput.get(out); }\n+\n+  let maxBit = 0;\n+  for (const g of gates) {\n+    for (const w of [g.in1, g.in2, g.out]) {\n+      if (w.startsWith('x') || w.startsWith('y')) {\n+        const n = parseInt(w.slice(1), 10);\n+        if (n > maxBit) maxBit = n;\n+      }\n+    }\n+  }\n+  const numBits = maxBit + 1;\n+\n+  function doSwap(wire1: string, wire2: string): void {\n+    swapped.add(wire1);\n+    swapped.add(wire2);\n+    const g1 = gateByOutput.get(wire1)!;\n+    const g2 = gateByOutput.get(wire2)!;\n+    g1.out = wire2;\n+    g2.out = wire1;\n+    gateByOutput.set(wire1, g2);\n+    gateByOutput.set(wire2, g1);\n+  }\n+\n+  let carry = '';\n+  for (let bit = 0; bit < numBits; bit++) {\n+    const xw = `x${String(bit).padStart(2, '0')}`;\n+    const yw = `y${String(bit).padStart(2, '0')}`;\n+    const zw = `z${String(bit).padStart(2, '0')}`;\n+\n+    if (bit === 0) {\n+      const xorGate = findGate('XOR', xw, yw);\n+      if (!xorGate) throw new Error(`Missing XOR gate for bit 0`);\n+      if (xorGate.out !== zw) doSwap(xorGate.out, zw);\n+      const andGate = findGate('AND', xw, yw);\n+      if (!andGate) throw new Error(`Missing AND gate for bit 0`);\n+      carry = andGate.out;\n+    } else {\n+      // Full adder tracing with swap detection at each stage\n+      const xorGate = findGate('XOR', xw, yw);\n+      let partialSum = xorGate.out;\n+      let sumGate = findGate('XOR', partialSum, carry);\n+\n+      if (!sumGate) {\n+        // Try zGate approach, then carry-based search, then partialSum-based search\n+        const zGate = gateFor(zw);\n+        if (zGate && zGate.op === 'XOR' && zGate !== xorGate) {\n+          // Match carry or partialSum to zGate inputs, swap the mismatch\n+          if (zGate.in1 === carry) { doSwap(partialSum, zGate.in2); partialSum = zGate.in2; sumGate = zGate; }\n+          else if (zGate.in2 === carry) { doSwap(partialSum, zGate.in1); partialSum = zGate.in1; sumGate = zGate; }\n+          else if (zGate.in1 === partialSum) { doSwap(carry, zGate.in2); carry = zGate.in2; sumGate = zGate; }\n+          else if (zGate.in2 === partialSum) { doSwap(carry, zGate.in1); carry = zGate.in1; sumGate = zGate; }\n+        }\n+        if (!sumGate) {\n+          // Find XOR using carry\n+          for (const g of gates) {\n+            if (g.op === 'XOR' && (g.in1 === carry || g.in2 === carry) && g !== xorGate) {\n+              const other = g.in1 === carry ? g.in2 : g.in1;\n+              doSwap(partialSum, other);\n+              partialSum = other;\n+              sumGate = g;\n+              break;\n+            }\n+          }\n+        }\n+        if (!sumGate) {\n+          // Find XOR using partialSum\n+          for (const g of gates) {\n+            if (g.op === 'XOR' && (g.in1 === partialSum || g.in2 === partialSum) && g !== xorGate) {\n+              const other = g.in1 === partialSum ? g.in2 : g.in1;\n+              doSwap(carry, other);\n+              carry = other;\n+              sumGate = g;\n+              break;\n+            }\n+          }\n+        }\n+      }\n+\n+      if (sumGate.out !== zw) doSwap(sumGate.out, zw);\n+\n+      const andGate = findGate('AND', xw, yw);\n+      const genCarry = andGate.out;\n+      const propGate = findGate('AND', partialSum, carry);\n+      const propCarry = propGate.out;\n+\n+      let orGate = findGate('OR', genCarry, propCarry);\n+      if (!orGate) {\n+        // Find OR gate using one of the carry wires\n+        for (const g of gates) {\n+          if (g.op === 'OR') {\n+            if (g.in1 === genCarry || g.in2 === genCarry) {\n+              const other = g.in1 === genCarry ? g.in2 : g.in1;\n+              doSwap(propCarry, other);\n+              orGate = g;\n+              break;\n+            }\n+            if (g.in1 === propCarry || g.in2 === propCarry) {\n+              const other = g.in1 === propCarry ? g.in2 : g.in1;\n+              doSwap(genCarry, other);\n+              orGate = g;\n+              break;\n+            }\n+          }\n+        }\n+      }\n+      carry = orGate.out;\n+    }\n+  }\n+  return [...swapped].sort();\n+}\n```\n\nProvide your findings categorized as HIGH PRIORITY, MEDIUM PRIORITY, or CONSIDER.","agentId":"a660ebb","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Now I have a thorough understanding of the code. Here is my complete review:\n\n---\n\n## Code Review: Circuit Simulator and Wire-Swap Debugger\n\n### HIGH PRIORITY\n\n#### 1. `simulate`: `result` variable used before definite assignment (line 38)\n\n**File:** `/workspace/src/index.ts`, lines 26-38\n\n```typescript\nlet result: number;\nswitch (gate.op) {\n  case 'AND': result = v1 & v2; break;\n  case 'OR':  result = v1 | v2; break;\n  case 'XOR': result = v1 ^ v2; break;\n}\nwires[gate.out] = result; // TypeScript strict: possibly unassigned\n```\n\nThe `switch` statement has no `default` case. While the `Gate` type constrains `op` to `'AND' | 'OR' | 'XOR'`, TypeScript's control flow analysis with `let result: number` and no `default` branch means `result` is technically possibly unassigned at line 38. Under `strict` / `strictNullChecks`, some TS configurations will flag this. More importantly, if the type system is ever circumvented (e.g., casting from parsed JSON), an unrecognized op would silently produce `undefined` being stored as a wire value, leading to downstream corruption rather than a clear error.\n\n**Recommendation:** Add a `default` case that throws an error, or initialize `result` to a sentinel and assert:\n\n```typescript\ndefault:\n  throw new Error(`Unknown gate operation: ${(gate as any).op}`);\n```\n\n#### 2. `simulate`: O(n^2) performance from `Array.splice` in a loop (lines 39, 21)\n\n**File:** `/workspace/src/index.ts`, line 39\n\n```typescript\nremaining.splice(i, 1);\n```\n\n`Array.splice` is O(n) because it shifts all subsequent elements. In the inner loop iterating over `remaining`, this produces O(n^2) behavior in the worst case across passes. For a 45-bit adder with ~220 gates, this is ~48,400 operations per pass -- manageable but wasteful. For larger circuits this would become a bottleneck.\n\n**Recommendation:** Use a `Set` of unprocessed gate indices, or rebuild the remaining array once per pass by filtering, or use topological sort for O(V+E) evaluation:\n\n```typescript\n// Option A: filter instead of splice\nconst nextRemaining: Gate[] = [];\nfor (const gate of remaining) {\n  // ... try to evaluate ...\n  if (!evaluated) nextRemaining.push(gate);\n}\nremaining = nextRemaining;\n```\n\n**Severity for 220 gates:** Low in practice (tests pass in <10ms), but the algorithmic concern is real.\n\n#### 3. `findSwappedWires`: Null dereference when `sumGate` is null at line 219\n\n**File:** `/workspace/src/index.ts`, line 219\n\n```typescript\nif (sumGate.out !== zw) doSwap(sumGate.out, zw);\n```\n\nThere is an explicit `if (!sumGate) throw new Error(...)` on line 216 that guards this. However, in the diff version shown in the problem statement, the `throw` guard on line 216 was **absent** -- the code jumped straight to `if (sumGate.out !== zw)`. Looking at the actual file, line 216 does contain the guard. The diff in the problem statement is a condensed version that omits lines 148 and 216, meaning **the diff as provided in the problem statement has a null-dereference bug at `sumGate.out`**. The actual source file is correct. This is worth flagging because if the diff is the source of truth, it is a crash.\n\nIn the diff:\n```diff\n+      if (!sumGate) {\n+        ...\n+      }\n+\n+      if (sumGate.out !== zw) doSwap(sumGate.out, zw);\n```\n\nBetween the last `if (!sumGate)` block (which does not throw or return) and line `if (sumGate.out !== zw)`, the variable `sumGate` can still be `undefined` if none of the three search strategies found a gate. The real file has a `throw` that prevents this, but in the diff it is missing.\n\n#### 4. `findSwappedWires`: Mutates the input `gates` array's objects (lines 117-118)\n\n**File:** `/workspace/src/index.ts`, lines 111-121\n\n```typescript\nfunction doSwap(wire1: string, wire2: string): void {\n  swapped.add(wire1);\n  swapped.add(wire2);\n  const g1 = gateByOutput.get(wire1)!;\n  const g2 = gateByOutput.get(wire2)!;\n  g1.out = wire2;  // Mutates the original Gate object\n  g2.out = wire1;  // Mutates the original Gate object\n  gateByOutput.set(wire1, g2);\n  gateByOutput.set(wire2, g1);\n}\n```\n\n`doSwap` mutates the `out` property of Gate objects from the input array. This means after `findSwappedWires` returns, the caller's `gates` array has been permanently modified. This is a surprising side effect for a function that appears to be a pure query (\"find swapped wires\"). If the caller subsequently uses the gates for simulation or calls `findSwappedWires` again, the gates are in a different state.\n\n**Recommendation:** Deep-clone the gates array at the top of `findSwappedWires`:\n\n```typescript\nconst gates = inputGates.map(g => ({ ...g }));\n```\n\n#### 5. `findSwappedWires`: `findGate` is O(n) linear scan, called multiple times per bit (lines 76-91)\n\n**File:** `/workspace/src/index.ts`, lines 76-91\n\n```typescript\nfunction findGate(op: string, in1: string, in2: string): Gate | undefined {\n  for (const g of gates) {\n    if (g.op === op && ((g.in1 === in1 && g.in2 === in2) || (g.in1 === in2 && g.in2 === in1))) {\n      return g;\n    }\n  }\n  return undefined;\n}\n```\n\n`findGate` does a linear scan over all ~220 gates every time it is called. It is called at least 4 times per bit (for XOR, XOR, AND, AND, OR), so for 45 bits that is ~220 * 45 * 5 = ~49,500 comparisons. This is fine for the current scale, but a `Map<string, Gate>` keyed on `{op}-{sorted_inputs}` would make each lookup O(1).\n\n**Severity for 220 gates:** Low (tests pass in <10ms), but worth noting for scalability.\n\n---\n\n### MEDIUM PRIORITY\n\n#### 6. `simulate`: Silent failure on unsolvable circuits\n\n**File:** `/workspace/src/index.ts`, lines 18-43\n\nIf gates have a dependency cycle or reference wires that never receive values, the `while` loop exits silently (when `changed` becomes `false` with `remaining.length > 0`). The function returns a partial result with no indication that some gates were not evaluated.\n\n**Recommendation:** After the loop, if `remaining.length > 0`, either throw an error or return the remaining gates alongside the partial result so the caller can detect the issue:\n\n```typescript\nif (remaining.length > 0) {\n  throw new Error(`${remaining.length} gates could not be evaluated (cycle or missing inputs)`);\n}\n```\n\n#### 7. `findSwappedWires`: `doSwap` does not update `findGate` search results\n\n**File:** `/workspace/src/index.ts`, lines 111-121 and 76-91\n\n`doSwap` updates `gateByOutput` (the output-to-gate map), but `findGate` searches by `(op, in1, in2)` -- it does not search by output. Since `doSwap` only changes `.out` properties and not `.in1`/`.in2`, `findGate` is unaffected. This is correct as-is, but the fact that the `gates` array is mutated (`.out` changes) means `findGate` is implicitly relying on the invariant that swaps only change outputs, never inputs. This is fragile and should be documented.\n\n#### 8. `findSwappedWires`: Missing null guard on `xorGate` 